data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

The EF Core Cosmos DB provider has been on a path to **remove synchronous API support entirely**. In .NET 10, the sync-over-async opt-in (e.g., `EnableSyncOverAsync()`) let you keep calling sync methods. In .NET 11, **that opt-in is removed** — all synchronous LINQ operations against the Cosmos provider throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime.

Every method in your repository is affected:

| Sync (breaks) | Async replacement |
|---|---|
| `.ToList()` | `.ToListAsync()` |
| `.First(...)` | `.FirstAsync(...)` |
| `.Count()` | `.CountAsync()` |
| `.SaveChanges()` | `.SaveChangesAsync()` |

### Fix: convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `Add()` stays synchronous — it only tracks the entity in memory, no I/O.
- All callers up the chain must also become `async`/`await` (it propagates).
- There is **no workaround** — the Cosmos provider's sync code paths are gone, not just gated behind a flag.
